issue.title: GeoJSON data not rendered after change
issue.body:
Please make sure to check the following boxes before submitting an issue. Thanks!

- [x] All peer dependencies are installed: React, ReactDOM and Leaflet.
- [x] Using a supported version of React and ReactDOM (v15.0.0+).
- [x] Using the supported version of Leaflet (v1.0.0) and its corresponding CSS file is loaded.
- [x] Using the latest version of React-Leaflet.
- [x] The issue has not already been reported.
- [x] Make sure you have followed the [quick start guide](http://leafletjs.com/examples/quick-start.html) for Leaflet.
- [x] Make sure you have fully read the [documentation](https://github.com/PaulLeCam/react-leaflet/blob/master/docs/README.md) and that you understand the [technical considerations](https://github.com/PaulLeCam/react-leaflet/blob/master/docs/How%20it%20works.md#limitations).

### Expected behavior
GeoJSON data should be re-rendered on the map after `data` prop change

### Actual behavior
GeoJSON data rendered only once. 

### Steps to reproduce
Create custom component with Map and GeoJSON components. Pass prop from custom component to GeoJSON component. Change prop. See that old data still rendered.
ex: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/44155385/rendering-geojson-with-react-leaflet

pull_request.title: CATTY-581 Crash when running "Geometry Dash v1.5"
pull_request.body:
https://jira.catrob.at/browse/CATTY-581

https://share.catrob.at/app/project/71c07dd2-cded-11ea-a5c3-005056a36f47

This project completely overwhelms our app and scheduling approach.

1. The xml file has 10MB and 232592 lines, causing hangs in the entire app because the parser takes a while
2. The first crash is our implementation of SynchonizedArray and FormulaCache, that hit the iOS stack size limit for secondary threads upon starting (https://developer.apple.com/forums/thread/111128)
3. Circumventing that by rewriting them to not use DispatchQueues but regular NSLocks, the main thread runs out of stack space
4. When increasing the main thread stack size via linker flag, it runs, with an amazing 14 FPS ...
